  "text": "Chromium's renderer process sandbox implementation spans multiple layers across Linux and Windows platforms. On Linux, the seccomp-BPF base policy is defined in sandbox/policy/linux/bpf_base_policy_linux.h/cc, which implements the BPFBasePolicy class that inherits from bpf_dsl::Policy. This enforces kernel attack surface reduction through syscall filtering. On Windows, the sandbox policy configuration is defined in sandbox/win/src/sandbox_policy.h, which contains the TargetPolicy class (line 263) that manages token levels, job objects, and other Windows-specific security constraints. The renderer process sandbox configuration is orchestrated in content/browser/renderer_host/renderer_sandboxed_process_launcher_delegate.h/cc through the RendererSandboxedProcessLauncherDelegate class, which implements GetSandboxType() to return the appropriate sandbox level. Windows-specific configuration is handled by RendererSandboxedProcessLauncherDelegateWin, which calls InitializeConfig() with Windows-specific policies. The sandbox types themselves are defined as an enum in sandbox/policy/mojom/sandbox.mojom, which includes kRenderer, kService, kGpu, kUtility, and others (62 types total). The sandbox/policy/sandbox_type.h/cc files provide mapping utilities like IsUnsandboxedSandboxType() and SetCommandLineFlagsForSandboxType() that manage the renderer sandbox lifecycle. The chain of execution flows from RendererSandboxedProcessLauncherDelegate::GetSandboxType() determining the sandbox level, which is then applied via SetCommandLineFlagsForSandboxType() and InitializeConfig() methods that configure the underlying BPF or Windows policies."
}

